1
00:00:00,880 --> 00:00:06,480
The human behavior in relation to money is 
always dominated by fear; greed, and hope.  

2
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:11,440
Well, candlestick analysis will help you to 
understand these changing psychological factors  

3
00:00:11,440 --> 00:00:15,040
by showing you how buyers and 
sellers interact with each other’s.  

4
00:00:15,040 --> 00:00:19,440
Candlesticks are basically a visual 
representation of what is going on in the market.  

5
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:24,320
By looking at a candlestick, you can get 
valuable information about the open, high,  

6
00:00:24,320 --> 00:00:28,800
low and the close of price, which will 
give you an idea about the price movement. 

7
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:33,680
In today’s video, you will discover how to 
recognize the most important candlestick patterns,  

8
00:00:33,680 --> 00:00:38,480
the psychology behind their formation, and what 
do they indicate when they form in the market. 

9
00:00:40,080 --> 00:00:45,760
First pattern is the engulfing candlestick.
This candlestick formation consists of two bodies,  

10
00:00:45,760 --> 00:00:50,480
the first body being smaller than the second 
one, in other words, the second body engulfs  

11
00:00:50,480 --> 00:00:55,440
the previous one. Here we can have a bearish 
engulfing bar and a bullish engulfing bar. 

12
00:00:56,320 --> 00:00:58,240
In case of a bearish engulfing bar,  

13
00:00:58,240 --> 00:01:01,600
this pattern tells us that sellers 
are in control of the market. 

14
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:07,280
When this pattern occurs at the end of an uptrend, 
this indicates that buyers are engulfed by sellers  

15
00:01:07,280 --> 00:01:12,320
which signals a potential trend reversal. 
Why is that? Because buyers are losing  

16
00:01:12,320 --> 00:01:16,240
control of the market, and sellers are 
trying to push the market to go down.
 
  

17
00:01:18,080 --> 00:01:23,360
The bullish engulfing bar pattern tells us that 
the market is no longer under control of sellers,  

18
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:26,960
and buyers are gaining strength.
When a bullish engulfing candle  

19
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:31,360
forms in the context of an uptrend, 
it indicates a continuation signal. 

20
00:01:31,360 --> 00:01:36,560
When a bullish engulfing candle forms at the end 
of a downtrend, it signals a potential reversal.
 

21
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,480
This example shows clearly how the market 
changes direction after the formation of a  

22
00:01:42,480 --> 00:01:47,120
bullish engulfing pattern. The smaller 
body that represents the selling power  

23
00:01:47,120 --> 00:01:51,040
was covered by the second body 
that represents the buying power. 

24
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:55,200
Very important: don’t try to trade the 
market using this price action setup alone,  

25
00:01:55,200 --> 00:02:00,080
because you will need other factors of confluence 
to decide whether the pattern is worth trading or  

26
00:02:00,080 --> 00:02:04,560
not. What I want you to do for now is to 
get the skill of identifying bearish and  

27
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:08,720
bullish engulfing bar on your charts. This 
is the most important step for the moment.

28
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:15,680
Second pattern is the Doji Candlestick pattern.
Doji is one of the most important Japanese  

29
00:02:15,680 --> 00:02:20,720
candlestick patterns, when this candlestick 
forms, it tells us that the market opens  

30
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:26,000
and closes at the same price which means that 
there is indecision between buyers and sellers,  

31
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:30,880
there is no one in control of the market.
The opening price is the same as the closing  

32
00:02:30,880 --> 00:02:36,000
price, this signal means that the market 
didn’t decide which direction will take.  

33
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:40,640
A doji could anticipate a reversal, or 
it can be a sign of consolidation.
 
  

34
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,800
This example shows how the 
market changed direction  

35
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:50,000
after the formation of the Doji candlestick.
The market was trending up, meaning that buyers  

36
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:55,360
had more strength. The formation of the Doji 
candlestick indicates that buyers are unable  

37
00:02:55,360 --> 00:03:01,520
to keep price higher, and sellers push prices 
back to the opening price. This is an indication  

38
00:03:01,520 --> 00:03:07,360
that a trend reversal is might be on the cards.
However, always remember that a Doji indicates  

39
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:11,600
indecision in the market, and you will 
often find it during periods of resting  

40
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:17,040
after big moves higher or lower.
 
 
Third pattern is the morning star. 

41
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:21,520
The morning star pattern is considered 
as a bullish reversal pattern,  

42
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:26,320
it often occurs at the bottom of a downtrend 
and it consists of three candlesticks: 

43
00:03:26,320 --> 00:03:30,640
-The first candlestick is bearish which 
indicates that sellers are still in charge. 

44
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:35,760
-The second candle is a small one which 
represents that sellers are in control,  

45
00:03:35,760 --> 00:03:40,320
but they don’t push the market much lower, 
and this candle can be bullish or bearish. 

46
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:46,240
-The third candle is a bullish candlestick 
that gapped up on the open and closed above the  

47
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:51,440
midpoint of the candle, and this candlestick 
holds a significant trend reversal signal. 

48
00:03:52,240 --> 00:03:56,960
The morning star pattern shows us how buyers 
took control of the market from sellers. 

49
00:03:56,960 --> 00:04:01,280
When this pattern occurs at the bottom 
of downtrend near a support level,  

50
00:04:01,280 --> 00:04:03,520
it signals a potential trend reversal.
 
 
  

51
00:04:05,040 --> 00:04:09,920
Here, the pattern occurred during an obvious 
bearish trend. The first candle confirmed  

52
00:04:09,920 --> 00:04:14,800
the seller’s domination, and the second 
one produces indecision in the market. 

53
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:19,440
Basically, the second candle indicated that 
sellers were struggling to push the market lower.  

54
00:04:20,080 --> 00:04:24,240
The third bullish candle indicates 
that buyers took control from sellers,  

55
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:30,240
and the market is likely to move upward.
 
Next is the evening star pattern 

56
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:34,160
The evening star pattern is considered 
as a bearish reversal pattern that  

57
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:39,920
usually occurs at the top of an uptrend.
The pattern also consists of three candlesticks: 

58
00:04:40,480 --> 00:04:45,440
-The first candle is a bullish candle
-The second candle is a small candlestick,  

59
00:04:45,440 --> 00:04:49,920
it can be bullish or bearish
-The third candle is a large bearish candle.  

60
00:04:50,640 --> 00:04:55,840
In general, the evening star pattern is the 
bearish version of the morning star pattern. 
  

61
00:04:56,960 --> 00:05:02,400
Here, the market was trending up, the first candle 
in the pattern indicating a trend continuation.  

62
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:08,160
The second one is a short candle indicating 
price consolidation and indecision.  

63
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:13,360
In other words, the trend that created the first 
long bullish candlestick is losing momentum. 

64
00:05:13,920 --> 00:05:17,760
The final candlestick moving lower than 
the previous candlestick indicates a  

65
00:05:17,760 --> 00:05:19,840
potential beginning of a new down move.
 
  

66
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:25,280
Another important candlestick 
formation is the hammer. 

67
00:05:25,280 --> 00:05:31,120
The Hammer candlestick is created when the 
open high and close are roughly the same price;  

68
00:05:31,120 --> 00:05:36,640
it is also characterized by a long lower shadow 
that indicates a bullish rejection from buyers  

69
00:05:36,640 --> 00:05:39,280
and their intention to push the market higher. 

70
00:05:39,280 --> 00:05:44,000
The hammer is a reversal candlestick pattern 
when it occurs at the bottom of a downtrend. 

71
00:05:44,560 --> 00:05:48,480
This candle forms when sellers push 
the market lower after the open,  

72
00:05:48,480 --> 00:05:53,200
but they get rejected by buyers so the market 
closes higher than the lowest price.
 
 
 

73
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:58,080
Here the market was trending down, 
and the formation of the hammer  

74
00:05:58,080 --> 00:06:02,800
represented a significant reversal pattern.
The long shadow represents the high buying  

75
00:06:02,800 --> 00:06:08,080
pressure from this point. Sellers were trying 
to push the market lower, but at that level,  

76
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:11,280
the buying pressure was more 
powerful than the selling pressure  

77
00:06:11,280 --> 00:06:16,000
which resulted in a price reversal.
The most important to understand is  

78
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:20,880
the psychology behind the formation of this 
pattern. If you can understand how and why  

79
00:06:20,880 --> 00:06:25,520
it was created, you will be able to anticipate 
the market direction with a higher accuracy.
 

80
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:30,640
The shooting star is another important 
reversal candlestick pattern. 

81
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:34,320
The shooting formation is 
formed when the open low,  

82
00:06:34,320 --> 00:06:39,440
and close are roughly the same price. This 
candle is characterized by a small body  

83
00:06:39,440 --> 00:06:43,680
and a long upper shadow. It’s basically 
the bearish version of the hammer.  

84
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:49,280
Very important: the shadow of the shooting star 
should be twice the length of the real body.
 
  

85
00:06:50,480 --> 00:06:55,920
This example shows a perfect shooting star with 
a real small body and an upper long shadow.  

86
00:06:55,920 --> 00:07:00,240
When this pattern occurs in an uptrend; 
it indicates a bearish reversal signal. 

87
00:07:01,040 --> 00:07:04,960
The psychology behind the formation 
of this pattern is that buyers tried  

88
00:07:04,960 --> 00:07:08,960
to push the market higher, but they 
got rejected by the selling pressure. 

89
00:07:08,960 --> 00:07:12,000
When this candlestick forms 
near a key resistance level,  

90
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:18,480
it should be taken as a high probability setup.
 
 
Another important formation is the inside bar. 

91
00:07:19,120 --> 00:07:23,680
The inside bar is a two bar candlestick 
pattern, which indicates price consolidation.  

92
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:29,520
In order to confirm this pattern you need to see 
a candle on the chart, which is fully contained  

93
00:07:29,520 --> 00:07:34,720
within the previous bar. In this manner, the 
inside bar candle should have a higher low  

94
00:07:34,720 --> 00:07:39,840
and a lower high than the previous candle.
This candlestick is considered a bearish  

95
00:07:39,840 --> 00:07:44,960
reversal signal when it occurs at the top of 
an uptrend, and it is a bullish signal when  

96
00:07:44,960 --> 00:07:50,480
it occurs at the bottom of a downtrend.
 
 
 
 
In this example, you can see how the trend  

97
00:07:50,480 --> 00:07:56,320
direction changes after the inside bar formation. 
The bullish inside bar pattern occurred at the  

98
00:07:56,320 --> 00:08:02,560
bottom of a downtrend. Here, sellers were pushing 
the market lower, price starts consolidating,  

99
00:08:02,560 --> 00:08:06,320
and this indicates that the selling power 
is no longer in control of the market.
 
 
  

100
00:08:07,920 --> 00:08:11,920
The bearish inside bar is the opposite 
of the bullish one, this one occurring  

101
00:08:11,920 --> 00:08:16,560
at the top of an uptrend indicating that 
buyer’s domination is losing strength  

102
00:08:16,560 --> 00:08:22,800
and the beginning of a downtrend is possible.
For me, since the inside candle has a lower high  

103
00:08:22,800 --> 00:08:27,760
and a higher low than the previous candlestick 
on the chart, this indicates consolidation. Bulls  

104
00:08:27,760 --> 00:08:34,080
cannot manage to create a higher high and at the 
same time the bears fail to create a lower low.  

105
00:08:34,080 --> 00:08:40,160
As such, there is not sufficient buying or selling 
pressure to break the previous bar’s high or low. 

106
00:08:40,160 --> 00:08:44,640
When this candlestick pattern happens during 
an uptrend or a downtrend, it’s probably  

107
00:08:44,640 --> 00:08:49,600
better to see it as a continuation pattern which 
offers a good opportunity to join the trend.
 
  

108
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:53,840
Tweezer top or bottom is another useful pattern. 

109
00:08:54,560 --> 00:08:59,760
Tweezers are reversal candlestick patterns that 
signal a potential change in the price direction. 

110
00:09:00,320 --> 00:09:05,360
The tweezer bottom candlestick pattern is a 
bullish reversal pattern that can be spotted  

111
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:11,200
at the bottom of a downtrend. It consists of 
two candles, where the first candle is in line  

112
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:16,240
with the bearish trend, while the second candle 
reflects more bullish market sentiment as the  

113
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:21,600
price moves higher, in the opposite direction.
If this price action happens near a key support  

114
00:09:21,600 --> 00:09:25,040
level, it indicates that a bullish 
reversal is likely to happen.
 
  

115
00:09:26,560 --> 00:09:32,000
The tweezer top candlestick pattern is of the same 
structure as the tweezer bottom, except for the  

116
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:37,760
fact that it happens at the end of an uptrend, and 
therefore, it is a bearish reversal pattern. The  

117
00:09:37,760 --> 00:09:43,360
first candle is bullish, and it continues in the 
same direction, while the second bearish candle  

118
00:09:43,360 --> 00:09:48,880
indicates that the trend may be changing soon.
The tweezers top occurs when buyers push the  

119
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:53,440
price higher, this gave us the impression 
that the market is still going up, but sellers  

120
00:09:53,440 --> 00:09:58,560
surprised buyers by pushing the market lower 
and close down the open of the bullish candle.
 
  

121
00:10:00,240 --> 00:10:04,960
These 2 patterns signal price reversals 
and we can trade them more efficient  

122
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:10,640
if we can combine them with other technical tools.
Both the bottom and top tweezers are only valid  

123
00:10:10,640 --> 00:10:15,840
when they occur during uptrends and downtrends. 
Their appearance during choppy trading conditions  

124
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:20,560
is practically meaningless, and it signals the 
market indecision to move in either direction.
 

125
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:27,280
Candlesticks are flexible, but they shouldn’t 
be used alone in your analysis. You don’t open  

126
00:10:27,280 --> 00:10:32,240
a buy position every time you spot a bullish 
engulfing candle and you don’t short the market  

127
00:10:32,240 --> 00:10:37,440
every time you see a shooting star. Candlestick 
patterns are best used in combination with support  

128
00:10:37,440 --> 00:10:43,360
and resistance, trend lines, and other technical 
tools such as the moving averages or pivot points.  

129
00:10:43,360 --> 00:10:48,080
Also, the time frame is very important. But we’ll 
discuss about these concepts in future videos. 

130
00:10:49,360 --> 00:10:53,680
If you found value and learned something new, 
leave us a like to show your support, subscribe  

131
00:10:53,680 --> 00:10:59,840
to our channel and hit the bell icon to be in 
touch when we upload new videos. Until next time.

